Escape from reality for just a little while, and invest yourself into the characterâ€™s lives, understand the way they feel. Which isnâ€™t hard, by the way The way Yii feels, how she always keeps busy, it makes total sense. Sheâ€™s the type of person who hides their pain. When her father died, she was sad. She said she didnâ€™t cry, but you know you miss them when you canâ€™t cry, in a way. She started doing jobs around the neighborhood, and she cut herself off from her family because she didnâ€™t want to expose that pain. text: 0:18 THE MAP.  In light of recent statements made by the Philippine government regarding Philippine sovereign rights in the West Philippine Sea, here comes another ambitious and insidious push from China.   Not only does Dreamworks' newest animation movie "Abominable" (a film about a magical yeti) show China's unilaterally declared nine-dash line in the West Philippine Sea, it also completely removed Mindanao and most of the Visayas from the map.  The film is a co-production between Dreamworks and Pearl Studio (formerly Oriental Dreamworks) based in Shanghai. The movie was partially made by a Chinese company, so it shouldn't be surprising they would use the map approved by China.  However, that shouldn't mean that as consumers we cannot do anything. We can express our frustration and vote with our wallets and refuse to go and watch this film. Vietnam has already pulled the movie from theaters. Philippines, your move.
